{"source_key":"sha256-d1b343ed42a51085ffb3fbb074863c4f","record_index":3198,"record_hash":"sha256:105e0e76581de5789aba429be20bcdd75a8ab592265960aa96349e4b3536a25a","timestamp":"2026-06-04T22:40:00.213Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yes. Not many expose “manual vs agent” directly, but good skills expose the same thing as a **control loop**: inspect state, choose an operation, act, verify, recover.\n\nBest examples:\n\n- **Claude Code `summarize-changes` skill**: injects live `git diff HEAD` before the agent responds, so the skill is grounded in workspace state, not generic instructions. That maps directly to `but status -fv` / branch state injection. [Claude docs](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/skills)\n\n- **GitHub Copilot Actions-debugging skill**: tells the agent to list workflow runs, summarize logs, fetch details if needed, reproduce, fix, then verify. That’s exactly the loop we want: state → diagnosis → action → verification. [GitHub docs](https://docs.github.[REDACTED:entropy]?hl=en-US)\n\n- **Data Analytics router skills**: expose a task menu and “good first prompts,” not raw tool docs. This is useful for GitButler: “commit this,” “ship it,” “split this into a branch,” “inspect what the agent did,” “recover stale IDs.” [OpenAI skills overview](https://openai.com/academy/skills/)\n\n- **Agent Skills standard examples**: the broader pattern is progressive disclosure: metadata first, full workflow only when relevant, scripts/resources only when needed. [Agent Skills](https://agentskills.io/home)\n\nFor GitButler, I’d steal the pattern, not the implementation:\n\n```md\n## GitButler Workspace Loop\n\nFor version-control tasks:\n1. Inspect: `but status -fv`\n2. Decide whether the task is commit, split, amend, uncommit, stack, push, or PR\n3. Act with the narrowest command\n4. Read returned status\n5. If leftovers remain, explain or continue only if it matches the user intent\n\nWhen the user asks what GitButler can do, offer tasks:\n- commit my changes\n- inspect what changed\n- split this work into another branch\n- amend/uncommit/move changes\n- stack or unstack branches\n- push/open PR\n- recover after failed IDs\n```\n\nOur current [GitButler skill]([REDACTED:path]) already has a lot of this: recipes, recovery, command mapping. The missing bit is a compact “workspace control surface” that teaches the agent to expose next actions after inspection, not just complete commits.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-06-04T22:40:00.213Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}